prompt:
Implement PR-B of the user-equipment-inventory feature for Flux: user inventory store wrapped in a Location envelope, Settings UI to edit equipment, constrained weight picker in the activity input, and an 'inventory drift' banner for exercises whose equipment is missing.

PR-A (already merged) added the app-level equipment catalog at src/data/equipmentCatalog.ts, extended Exercise with equipmentRequired/equipmentAlternatives, and added a warnings channel to validateProgramSchema with an InventoryView shape. Build on that.

## Scope

### 1. User inventory store with Location envelope

In src/tabs/Workouts/state.ts:

- Bump DB_VERSION from 2 → 3. Add INVENTORY_STORE = 'inventory' to the openDb stores list (alongside STATE_STORE, LOG_STORE, PROGRAM_STORE).
- Single record at key 'current' holding the full LocationsState (same pattern as STATE_STORE).
- Default seed when no record exists:
  ```
  { locations: { default: { id: 'default', name: 'Home', inventory: {} } },
    activeLocationId: 'default' }
  ```

Types live in a new src/data/inventory.ts:

```ts
import type { EquipmentKind } from './equipmentCatalog';

export interface InventoryItem {
  kind: EquipmentKind;
  // Discrete weights the user owns, in lbs. Empty array for kinds where
  // hasWeightSelection is false (TRX, pullup bar, bodyweight, etc.).
  ownedWeights: number[];
  note?: string;
}

export type Inventory = Partial<Record<EquipmentKind, InventoryItem>>;

export interface Location {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  inventory: Inventory;
}

export interface LocationsState {
  locations: Record<string, Location>;
  activeLocationId: string;
}

export const DEFAULT_LOCATIONS_STATE: LocationsState = {
  locations: { default: { id: 'default', name: 'Home', inventory: {} } },
  activeLocationId: 'default',
};

// Convenience selector — read the inventory of the active location.
export function activeInventory(state: LocationsState): Inventory {
  return state.locations[state.activeLocationId]?.inventory ?? {};
}

// True when the user has populated inventory in any location. Used to
// gate constrained-picker behaviour — first-run users keep the old free
// input until they've configured something.
export function isInventoryConfigured(state: LocationsState): boolean {
  return Object.values(state.locations).some(
    (loc) => Object.keys(loc.inventory).length > 0,
  );
}
```

New API in src/tabs/Workouts/state.ts:
- `loadLocations(): Promise<LocationsState>` — returns DEFAULT_LOCATIONS_STATE clone when no record.
- `saveLocations(s: LocationsState): Promise<void>`
- Include INVENTORY_STORE in clearAll().
- Sanitize loaded data the same way loadState does (defensive parsing — don't trust IDB blobs blindly).

### 2. Equipment-resolution helper

New file src/tabs/Workouts/logic/equipmentResolve.ts:

```ts
// Returns the sorted-ascending list of weights the user can use for this
// exercise's equipment.
//   - null  → exercise doesn't use weight at all (no constraint)
//   - []    → exercise needs weight but user owns no compatible equipment
//   - [...] → owned weights, deduped, sorted ascending
export function allowedWeightsForExercise(ex: Exercise, inv: Inventory): number[] | null

// Returns true when the user owns enough equipment (any of equipmentRequired
// OR any equipmentAlternatives group fully satisfied). 'bodyweight' is
// always considered owned.
export function isExerciseSupportedByInventory(ex: Exercise, inv: Inventory): boolean
```

Honor equipmentAlternatives correctly: if the primary equipmentRequired set isn't fully owned, try each alternative group; first match wins. For allowedWeights, union the ownedWeights of every owned kind that contributes (e.g., if user owns both KB and DB, KB-row offers the union — sorted/deduped).

### 3. Settings UI — new Equipment section

In src/tabs/Settings.tsx, add a new card between LLM provider and Data sections:

- Title: 'Equipment'
- Subtitle: 'What you have available for workouts. Programs and weight pickers respect this.'
- Lists the EQUIPMENT_CATALOG entries grouped by category (free-weight / fixed / cardio / accessory). Hide 'bodyweight' from the UI — it's always implicitly owned.
- Each row: a toggle 'Owned' + (when checked AND hasWeightSelection) a weight chip editor below.
- Weight chip editor:
  - Existing weights render as removable chips (× to remove).
  - Number input + 'Add' button to insert a new weight.
  - One-click 'preset' dropdown per kind. Sensible defaults:
    - kettlebell: 'Common set (25/35/45)', 'Light (10/15/20)', 'Heavy (35/45/55/70)'
    - dumbbell: 'Adjustable 5-50 by 5', 'Adjustable 5-90 by 5'
    - barbell: 'Olympic + plates', leave the actual plate math to the user — just default to 45/65/85/etc.
  - Validate: positive numbers only, dedup, store sorted ascending.
- Free-text 'Note' field per item (small input).
- Saves to IDB on every change (debounce 250ms is fine, or save on blur/Enter — match the lightweight feel of the existing mode toggle).
- DO NOT show a location picker — the LocationsState wrapper is there for future multi-location work but the UI only edits locations[activeLocationId].inventory in this PR.

Existing Tailwind aesthetic — match the rounded-[2rem] cards, the [10px] uppercase-tracked headings, the bg-flux-soft chips, etc. No new components library.

### 4. Activity input — constrained weight picker

In src/tabs/Workouts/components/ExerciseCard.tsx (currently lines 179-217 hold the weight controls):

- Accept two new props: `allowedWeights: number[] | null` and `inventoryConfigured: boolean`.
- When inventoryConfigured is false: keep today's free-input picker exactly as-is. Don't surprise first-run users.
- When inventoryConfigured is true AND allowedWeights is a non-empty list:
  - Replace the free \<input type=number\> with a horizontal scroll-snap chip strip (or compact \<select\>) over allowedWeights. The selected chip uses bg-flux-accent / text-flux-accent-fg styling.
  - Keep + / − buttons but step to the next/previous owned weight rather than ±increment.
  - If the entry's currently-logged weight isn't in allowedWeights (drift: user previously logged 25 lbs but sold the 25), still render that weight as an extra chip with subtle styling (e.g., border instead of fill, plus a small 'not in inventory' badge using the existing 'Unmapped' chip pattern). New selections from + / − stay within allowedWeights.
- When inventoryConfigured is true AND allowedWeights is empty: drop the weight controls entirely (the banner from step 6 covers the UX).
- allowedWeights null is unchanged from today (exercise.usesWeight already gates rendering).

In src/tabs/Workouts/logic/progression.ts:
- Update suggestWeight to take an optional allowedWeights param. When supplied, snap the suggested value DOWN to the highest owned weight ≤ the unconstrained suggestion. Never suggest a weight the user doesn't own.

### 5. Wire inventory through Workouts/index.tsx

- Load LocationsState alongside state/log/program in the existing useEffect (extend the Promise.all).
- Compute `inv = activeInventory(loc)` and `configured = isInventoryConfigured(loc)` from the loaded state.
- For each resolvedExercise, compute `allowedWeights = allowedWeightsForExercise(catalogEntry, inv)` and `supported = isExerciseSupportedByInventory(catalogEntry, inv)`. Pass through to ExerciseCard.
- Note: resolvedExercise loses the original Exercise after the resolve step — you'll need to either include equipmentRequired/equipmentAlternatives in ResolvedExercise, or look the catalog entry up again. Extending ResolvedExercise is cleaner (just two more fields, both optional).

### 6. Inventory drift banner

Above each ExerciseCard, when `configured && !supported`, render a one-line muted banner:

> 'Requires kettlebell — not in your inventory.'

Use a list-comma-and-or join when multiple equipment kinds are missing. Style: rounded-2xl bg-flux-soft px-3 py-2 text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-flux-text-tertiary. Place it ABOVE the ExerciseCard (not inside) so the card's existing visual weight isn't disturbed.

If !configured, never show the banner — drift is meaningless when no inventory is set.

### 7. Export / Import round-trip

In src/tabs/Workouts/logic/exportImport.ts:

- Extend ExportPayload (in types.ts) with optional `locations?: LocationsState`.
- exportPayload() includes the loaded LocationsState when isInventoryConfigured returns true (no point exporting the empty default).
- applyImport() and applyImportFromFile() accept locations: sanitize defensively (drop unknown EquipmentKind keys, coerce weights to numbers, dedup, sort), then saveLocations(). Treat absence as 'don't touch the current inventory' — never wipe existing inventory on an import that lacks the field.
- Update formatImportMessage() so it mentions inventory restoration when present.

### 8. Tests

Add to tests/workouts.spec.ts (or split into a new tests/inventory.spec.ts if it keeps things readable):

- Golden path: user opens Settings, toggles kettlebell on, adds weights 25/35/45 via the chip editor, returns to Workouts tab. The goblet-squats card now offers only 25/35/45 in the weight chip strip. + button cycles 25 → 35 → 45 and stops. Free-text input is no longer present.
- Drift banner: after the above, user removes the 25 chip; revisits Workouts; an old log entry that recorded 25 lbs still renders the 25 chip but marked subtly, while new selections only offer 35/45.
- Equipment missing: user toggles kettlebell off entirely; the goblet-squats card shows the drift banner above it and no weight controls.
- First-run fallback: with the default empty inventory, the Workouts tab behaves exactly like today (free input, no banners). This is the regression check that protects existing users.
- Export/import round-trip: configure inventory, export, fresh DB, import, inventory restored verbatim.

Where component-level tests are awkward in Playwright, supplement with unit tests for allowedWeightsForExercise and isExerciseSupportedByInventory (cover the alternatives logic and bodyweight sentinel).

## Constraints & repo conventions (from CLAUDE.md and README)

- NEVER push to main. Open a PR.
- NEVER reference Claude in commits / PR titles / PR descriptions.
- Use nix for ALL commands: `nix develop --command npm …` and `nix develop .#test --command npx playwright test`.
- Run the test suite (nix develop .#test --command npm test) before opening the PR and fix any failures. Prefer integration / e2e tests over heavy mocking — drive the Settings UI end-to-end and assert what the user sees.
- TypeScript strict mode — no `any`, narrow types, keep the isObject helper pattern from programSchema.ts.
- No new dependencies.
- Hand-roll the chip components — no UI library, per the umbrella plan.

## Out of scope (DO NOT touch)

- src/llm/* — planner integration is PR-C.
- prompts/generate-phase.md — planner rewrite is PR-C.
- The location PICKER UI. The LocationsState wrapper is in place but the user never sees a location concept in this PR. Forward-compat only.
- Renaming or migrating existing IDB stores beyond the additive bump to v3.

